<p>
The night before the established day, residents put the bags outside.
There aren't garbage bins - trash bags stay for a night outside before
collection. In my neighbourhood roads are large and well kept, but houses
don't seem well built; most of them are wooden. It is obvious that in
these conditions there are problems with rats and other undesired
visitors. I wonder how the Japanese - which are very picky about hygiene
issues, for example they wear a mask when they have flu - can stand these
problems. 

</p>
<p>
  The solution strikes me as lightning obvious. Placing an advanced
  device called "garbage bin" in the streets would eliminate the rotting
  of trash on the apartments' terraces, the proliferation of the friendly
  pets and therefore the need for (unhealthy!) poisons and traps
  scattered through the house. But then again, maybe I can't grasp what
  is the logic behind this.
</p>
